04653nam a22006855i 9780292734760DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212011txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927347607 a10.7560/7239862doi  a(DE-B1597)588754  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF1465.2.T9bC37 2011 7aSOC0000002bisacsh1 aCarlsen, Robert S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe War for the Heart and Soul of a Highland Maya Town :bRevised Edition /cRobert S. Carlsen. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (249 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tForeword: Complex Performance in Santiago Atitlan -- tPreface to the Revised Edition -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART ONE ESTABLISHING PLACE AND IMAGINING COMMUNITY -- t1. What in the World Is Going On in Santiago Atitlán? -- t2. The Atiteco Mayas at the End of the Twentieth Century -- t3. The Flowering of the Dead -- tPART TWO HISTORY, PERIPHERALITY, AND SOCIAL PLURALISM -- t4. Conquest and Adaptation in Santiago Atitlán -- t5. On Enlightenment, Liberalism, and Ladinos -- tPART THREE Death of Community, Resurrection of Autonomy -- t6. Under the Gun in Santiago Atitlán -- t7. When Immortals Die -- t8. Season of the Witch: The New Millennium in Santiago Atitlán -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis compelling ethnography explores the issue of cultural continuity and change as it has unfolded in the representative Guatemala Mayan town Santiago Atitlán. Drawing on multiple sources, Robert S. Carlsen argues that local Mayan culture survived the Spanish Conquest remarkably intact and continued to play a defining role for much of the following five centuries. He also shows how the twentieth-century consolidation of the Guatemalan state steadily eroded the capacity of the local Mayas to adapt to change and ultimately caused some factions to reject—even demonize—their own history and culture. At the same time, he explains how, after a decade of military occupation known as la violencia, Santiago Atitlán stood up in unity to the Guatemalan Army in 1990 and forced it to leave town. This new edition looks at how Santiago Atitlán has fared since the expulsion of the army. Carlsen explains that, initially, there was hope that the renewed unity that had served the town so well would continue. He argues that such hopes have been undermined by multiple sources, often with bizarre outcomes. Among the factors he examines are the impact of transnational crime, particularly gangs with ties to Los Angeles; the rise of vigilantism and its relation to renewed religious factionalism; the related brutal murders of followers of the traditional Mayan religion; and the apocalyptic fervor underlying these events.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aSocial changezGuatemalazSantiago Atitlán. 0aTzutuhil IndiansxReligion. 0aTzutuhil IndiansxSocial conditions. 0aTzutuhil philosophy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aCarrasco, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarrasco, Davíd.1 aPrechtel, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrechtel, Martín.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/72398640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292734760423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292734760/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK